$add = mysql_query("INSERT INTO `articles` VALUES (1, 'User Documentation', 'GiveMeHelp.net', 'Creative Staff', '<pre>\r\n\r\nGiveMeHelp.net Content Manager\r\n			User Documentation\r\nVersion 0.8 (codename: the-nexus.org content manager) \r\n\r\nContents:\r\n•	Introduction Paragraph\r\n•	Setting Up\r\n•	Initial Use\r\n•	The  Administrator Functions\r\no	General\r\n&#61607;	Administration Index\r\n&#61607;	Members Index\r\n&#61607;	General Settings\r\n&#61607;	Menu Links\r\no	Administration\r\n&#61607;	Add an Administrator\r\n&#61607;	Edit an Administrator\r\no	Articles\r\n&#61607;	Add an Article\r\n&#61607;	Edit an Article\r\n&#61607;	Categories\r\n&#61607;	View Member’s Articles\r\n&#61607;	Delete an Article\r\no	Groups\r\n&#61607;	Add a Member Group\r\n&#61607;	Edit a Member Group\r\n&#61607;	Delete a Member Group\r\no	Homepage\r\n&#61607;	Add a Homepage\r\n&#61607;	Edit a Homepage\r\n&#61607;	Delete a Homepage\r\no	Members\r\n&#61607;	Add a Member\r\n&#61607;	Edit a Member\r\n&#61607;	List all Member\r\n&#61607;	Delete a Member\r\n&#61607;	IP Ban Wizard\r\no	Skins\r\n&#61607;	Add a Skin\r\n&#61607;	Edit a Skin\r\n&#61607;	Delete a Skin\r\n•	The Member Functions\r\no	Site\r\n&#61607;	Articles\r\n&#61607;	Categories\r\n&#61607;	Members\r\n&#61607;	Submit An Article\r\no	Settings\r\n&#61607;	Profile\r\n&#61607;	Inbox\r\n•	Uninstallation\r\n•	Upgrade\r\n•	Support\r\n\r\n\r\nIntroduction Paragraph\r\n\r\nWelcome to the official user documentation for the GMH Content Manager. The<br> \r\nmanager was designed to bring a greater level of ease to website design <br>\r\nand maintenance. This documentation will cover the basics right down to <br>\r\nthe advance capabilities of the system, along with set up instructions <br>\r\nfor first time users. <br>\r\n\r\nSetting Up\r\n\r\nBy now you should have the GMH Content Manager zip folder, containing the<br>\r\nsoftware. Choose whether you wish to upload it to your web space via the <br>\r\nfile manager or an FTP client, and upload the file directly to your <br>\r\npublic_html file. Extract the file and open up the read_me.txt file that <br>\r\naccompanies this file, for more in depth set up instructions.<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n	Initial Use\r\n\r\nOk, so now you are set up, its time to start using your new software.<br> You <br>should have set your root administrators username and password<br> in the global_conf.php file, so now its time to access the admin panel<br> for the <br>first time. On the address bar type in <br> {your_site}/admin/index.php you should now be presented with a log<br> in screen, where you can enter your <br>details, and click ‘log in’.\r\n\r\n	The Administrator Functions\r\n\r\nFrom here onwards, this documentation will explain each of the functions<br> available to you in this particular version build of the Content Manager.<br>\r\n\r\n		General\r\n			Administration Index\r\nThe first thing you will notice is the notes portion of the page,<br> this section is a shared area between all administrators, so anything you<br> write and save here, will be visible to all other members that have<br> access to the admin panel.\r\n\r\n			Members Index\r\nThis option within your admin panel will direct you to the member view<br> of your site, although you can easily return to your admin panel from<br> the member index.\r\n		\r\n\r\n			General Settings\r\nThe general settings will allow you to configure your system for all<br> those that use all elements, be it administrator or member.<br> \r\n\r\n			Menu Links\r\nMenu links will allow you to add new sections to the administration<br> panel, so that you can customise it to how you want. You can choose to<br> edit and/or create a new link and a new category.\r\n\r\n		Administration\r\n			Add an Administrator \r\nWith this function you can allow new users access to your administration<br>\r\n panel, allow caution is advised, as once you appoint an admin they<br> can do anything except delete the root administrator. This is a safety<br> feature we can implemented to avoid the root administrator from being<br> ejected from their own website.\r\n\r\n			Edit an Administrator\r\nHere you can edit the powers and details of any existing administrator,<br> although, the root account can only be edited by the root administrator.<br>\r\n\r\n		Articles\r\n			Add an Article\r\n‘Add an article’ allows you to publish an article into the public section<br>\r\nof your website. If a member creates an article, it will automatically<br> enter a pending state, the article then has to be approved by an <br>\r\nAdministrator or a member of the editorial staff. Guests can also submit<br> in a similar fashion is guest submittal is turned on,<br> in the general settings.\r\n\r\n			Edit an Article\r\nThe edit article feature allows you to do a number of things, search an article by various criteria such as: author; editor and title. Or you can choose to list all available articles, and then you can select an article to edit, and change or revise any of the articles content. \r\n\r\n			Categories\r\nThis section will allow you to categorise your articles, to make them easier to locate, if you create a new category, it will become available for selection immediately. You can also go back to the article edit stage, and re-assign an articles category.\r\n\r\n			View Member’s Articles\r\nOnce a member creates an article, it will need to be approved by either an Administrator or a member of the editorial staff, this is the section you will need to visit to approve all these articles. \r\n\r\n			Delete an Article\r\nQuite simple this is where you can remove articles that either violate your websites policies, or are no longer required.\r\n\r\n		Groups\r\n			Add a Member Group\r\nFrom this option, you can create an unlimited number of user groups that you can assign your members to. You can also dictate what powers and functionality that user group will be granted upon creation.\r\n\r\n			Edit a Member Group\r\nThis feature will allow you to revise what powers and abilities each member group can access and use. \r\n\r\nDelete a Member Group\r\nIf you decide a certain member group is no longer required, you can delete them completely via the use of this option.\r\n\r\n		Homepage\r\n			Add a Homepage\r\nEach member group will be able to access their own homepage; this feature will allow you to add a homepage for each level of membership.\r\n\r\n			Edit a Homepage\r\nBy default each member group will be assigned a standard GiveMeHelp style homepage, via the use of this edit tool you can edit the pages to your own tastes.\r\n\r\n			Delete a Homepage\r\nIf you wish to completely remove a homepage, then use this delete option, and it will be erased from the database.\r\n\r\n		Members\r\n			Add a Member\r\nAlthough there is a registration option, you may wish to manually add a member. This option will allow you to enter all the member’s credentials, or just enter core details, and allow them to edit the rest at a later date. \r\n\r\n			Edit a Member\r\nFrom time to time you may need to edit data relating to your members, this edit feature will allow you to do so, and to also reassign their member group.\r\n\r\n			List all Members\r\nKeeping track of your members is no easy task, this list all feature allows you to quickly see an overview of everyone registered to your system.\r\n\r\n			Delete a Member\r\nTroublesome members every now and then will need to be erased from the system, and this option will allow you to do so,\r\n\r\n			IP Ban Wizard\r\nThis handy little tool will allow you to IP ban anyone you desire, from accessing your website, and although it does offer a wild card function, we cannot guarantee complete efficiency due to the ability to mask IP addresses.\r\n\r\n		Skins\r\n			Add a Skin\r\nAs you grow more adept with the admin panel, you may wish to add your own custom theme for the panel, this can be done easily with the add a skin option.\r\n	\r\n			Edit a Skin\r\nWhen you obtain the Content Manager, you will be given a default selection of our skins, but you can adjust these, or edit skins you have created yourself.\r\n\r\n			Delete a Skin\r\nIf a skin doesn’t quite fit the standards you need, you can delete it with this option.\r\n\r\n	The Member Functions\r\n\r\nThis portion of the manual will give you an overview of what functions and features are available to your sites members.\r\n\r\n		Site\r\n			Articles\r\n‘Articles’ allows visitors to browse through your sites collection of articles that you have made available for public viewing in your admin panel.\r\n\r\n			Categories\r\nTo add a little more order, to what could be anarchy, we have incorporated a categories option, so that you can easily categorise your articles into manageable sections. And further more, allow your users to narrow down what they are looking for.\r\n\r\n			Members\r\nHere your users will be able to view the personal profiles of other members of your site, as well as send them a personal message or find out what articles that member has submitted to the site.\r\n\r\n			Submit An Article\r\nThis is it, the most fundamental element of your new site, with this powerful tool your members will be able to easily create an article, submit it to you or your editorial staff, have it approved, and then it will be made available in the public area of your site. This element has specifically design to work for all levels of coding and computer knowledge, so that anybody can use it.\r\n\r\n		Settings\r\n			Profile\r\nAs you would expect when you join a site, you are allowed a custom profile area, this is no different, members will be able to add as much or as little information about themselves on their profile, the only mandatory fields upon registration are a valid email address, and a password that is not widely known. Members will be able to assign themselves an avatar and a signature that will appear alongside their published articles. \r\n\r\n			Inbox\r\nOur system aims to heighten user interactivity, and in an effort to do so, we have included a personal messenger system. Members will be able to contact each other with this handy tool. \r\n\r\n	Uninstallation\r\n\r\nIf for some reason you are not satisfied with the Content Manager, you can uninstall it via the following steps. First of all ensure you have duplicated any information you wish to retain, then open the mySQL editor, and remove the database you affiliated the software with, next open either the file manager or your FTP client and delete the file named ‘Manager’, now the system has been completely removed from your web space.\r\n\r\n	Upgrade\r\n\r\nPeriodically we may decide to release upgrades and modifications to our Content Management System, These upgrades will be released with their own revised user documentation that will guide you step by step through the upgrades, we will try to ensure that these upgrades are as simple as possible to implement. \r\n\r\n	Support\r\n\r\nSince we are aware it is impossible to create a completely erroneous free piece of software, we have created a discussion forum where you can request assistance (support.givemehelp.net) or you can email techsupport@givemehelp.net for more assistance. \r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>', 0, 0, '', '', 0, 3)")or die("<br>Please contact <a href='http://givemehelp.net'>GiveMeHelp.net</a> immediately.<br>" . mysql_error());
